			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Statistics are <span style="font-style: italic">counter intuitive</span>. Which is a fancy highfalutin' word that means: 1) it is hard to understand and 2) what you think will happen does not match what will happen. The only philosophical problem is that some people believe that what has happened in the past is a predictor of what will happen in the future, and other people who believe that the future has zero link with the past (which is why some folks reach for their gun when they hear about Bayesian Statistics). If you want to read a decent history of the development of statistics, read <a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0471295639/" target="_blank" class="postlink">Against The Gods</a>. If you want to get an idea why people routinely lose fortunes in the stock market, read <a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/0465043550/" target="_blank" class="postlink">The Misbehavior of Markets</a>.
<br />

<br />
The gambling, derivative and insurance industries make huge profits every year because people are: poor at math, cannot <span style="font-style: italic">do statistics</span> and/or believe that past results have no influence on future events. Because it is important to determine future events from historical data, Wall Street spends billions of dollars every year on statistics and wizzkid econometricitians trying to gain even the slightest edge. Some predictions border on voodoo, like the Japanese and their obsession with predicting earthquakes (vs making buildings able to stand up to quakes, long enough that folks can evacuate them, like in the states) or with the data mining for "homeland security."
<br />

<br />
Recently, there was a round of articles and papers on <span style="font-style: italic">the monty hall scenario</span>. While it sounds stupid, or silly, it really highlighted whether people can reason correctly about statistical questions. The problem goes like this... On the game show "lets make a deal" there is a scenario where a contestant is offered a choice of 3 doors. Door #1, door #2 and door #3. They chose one. Monty Hall then opens another door (showing a booby prize like a goat or last years newspapers) and asks the contestant if they want to switch. The question goes <span style="font-style: italic">does the contestant's chance of winning go up or down if they switch, and why?</span> One, popular but incorrect answer is that the contestant has 1/3 chance of winning if they don't switch, and 1/2 chance of winning if they do switch.
<br />

<br />
Notation:
<br />
XYZ=W/L means the prize is behind door X, the contestant chose door Y and Monty opened door Z. Monty opening the door the prize is behind (before the contestant choses to stand or switch) is impossible, so combinations where X=Z are impossible. W win, L = loss. D = don't care (meaning the number in that location is irrelevant).
<br />

<br />
The incorrect logic goes something like this: if you pick a door at random, and the prize is behind another random door, then you have a 1 in 3 chance of winning the prize. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline">Standing</span>
<br />
112=W
<br />
113=W
<br />
123=L
<br />
132=L
<br />
213=L
<br />
221=W
<br />
223=W
<br />
231=L
<br />
312=L
<br />
321=L
<br />
331=W
<br />
332=W
<br />

<br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline">Switching</span>
<br />
112=L
<br />
113=L
<br />
123=W
<br />
132=W
<br />
213=W
<br />
221=L
<br />
223=L
<br />
231=W
<br />
312=W
<br />
321=W
<br />
331=L
<br />
332=L
<br />

<br />
Whether you switch or not, there are 6 possible wins and 6 possible losses. But part of what makes the math hard, is that not all of the possibilities have an equal chance of happening. Assumptions: 1) there is a 1/3 chance the prize is behind door #A , 2) you are not given the correct door (i.e. the game is honest) and 3) you are picking numbers at random (careful studying of past episodes will prove whether that assumption is valid).</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
