				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">not having read everyone's arguing beyond the first post, here's my reply to the first post.   
<br />

<br />
Michael Moore packed so many different perspectives and opinions in Farenheight 9/11 that calling it an anti-bush movie is an oversimplification. There is that yes, but if that's all you see you're missing most of the film. What I walked away with more than anything was that war is not to be entered lightly, as war sucks. Was what I walked away with what MM intended people to walk away with? Oh, at least 10 mins of the film was about that. And every 10 mins of the film was about something else. Some I agreed with, some I didn't. The film is an interesting film, and potentialy thought provoking if you watch it with an attitude of neither "boo conservaitves!" or "boo liberals!" which almost everyone speaking about the film seems to be unable to overcome. 
<br />

<br />
Certainly the military spends a lot of resources in recruitment. Corperate headhunters get paid a lot too. As do temp agencys, monster.com, ect. Employment is a big buisness. Some advertise better than others, and the US Military has a pretty good ad campaing going for it. They offer college scholorships, but so do a lot of other companies. The military advertises it in schools. People that don't look beyond what is advertised to them are likely to buy into that. People that investigate their options are less likely to buy into that. And of course people who's parents tell them they have endless options about how to live their life to be a sucesss are less likely to buy into the military career.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
