				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Certainly the military spends a lot of resources in recruitment. Corperate headhunters get paid a lot too. As do temp agencys, monster.com, ect. Employment is a big buisness. Some advertise better than others, and the US Military has a pretty good ad campaing going for it. They offer college scholorships, but so do a lot of other companies. The military advertises it in schools. People that don't look beyond what is advertised to them are likely to buy into that. People that investigate their options are less likely to buy into that. And of course people who's parents tell them they have endless options about how to live their life to be a sucesss are less likely to buy into the military career.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
For the most part you are correct Pyro, but let me hit you with another thought.
<br />
The military pays for ALL schooling for the job you are going to do for them. How many other jobs do that? Currently, the military and programs in place will pay for almost 100% college tuition if you take classes in your spare time, which for alot of people spare time includes while at work on duty. How many jobs will let you do your college work on the clock during down time? 
<br />
The military covers your medical and dental, and offers some of the cheapest family prices you will ever find, such as no charge at a military hospital. Between my wife's hospital stay for the birth of 2 kids, I payed a $25 co-pay for the civilian hospital stay with the first child. That was it.
<br />
Being the nature of the job, you also get the some of the cheapest life insurance you could ever find and your spouse can be covered as well.  Difference between the civilian world is that for military life insurance you need to be on active duty(or the spouse), and they don't pay attention to your current health or lifestyle to determine price, it is a flat rate for all.
<br />
I could go into more detail, but I will paraphrase what someone said on these boards recently. The benefits are good, if you can live without alot of spending money.
<br />
So to say those that investigate their options more and pick the military less, i would think those people arent investigating what the military offers, only what they can find elsewhere. Don't talk about the military as if the only people that join were too dumb to check their other options. Some people do it because they want to and don't care about the other options.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
